post_text:
Dear PUHSD families, staff and communities:

I hope you enjoy this last newsletter of the 2019-2020 school year -- and what a year it's been. We know the past few months have been difficult, and we hope you have all found ways to experience some joy along the way.

This newsletter includes photos our students and teachers shared with us during the shelter-in-place orders, along with our thanks to our amazing PUHSD Nutrition Services team who always ensures our students have healthy, nutritious meals. And finally, this issue is dedicated to our MOST amazing, resilient Class of 2020 who never anticipated spending their last term the way they did. But they rose above it, and we are so very proud of them.

Enjoy your summer!

Kristin Conner, Public Information Officer
Foresthill High School Colfax High School Placer High School Del Oro Confluence High School Maidu Virtual Charter Academy @PlacerSchoolForAdults

shared_text:
Michelle Junso Guardino is with Nic F Russo and 48 others at Del Oro High School.
April 28 at 10:48 AM ¬∑ Loomis, CA ¬∑

üñ§üíõA four day caravan of DO love by a group of administrators and leadership teachers (and our families) paying a surprise visit to all 70 Del Oro teachers at their homes. We played the fight song and cheered uproariously as we delivered a care package of love, gratitude, toilet paper, a Rock Star energy drink, and a pack of yellow flower seeds. Over 300 miles and almost 30 hours of driving, a handful of tears (I'm not crying you're crying) and enough love to lift our spirits through this crazy time.Carson Zerwas put together this video https://youtu.be/jlrmRpl17wo of the journey ... grab a tissue and enjoy! üíõüñ§

Welcome back from spring break PUHSD!

Don't forget that our awesome Food Nutrition Services team is back and ready to serve up hot, nutritious lunches for all students under 18!

We will continue this food service delivery through the end of the school year. Students are welcome to pick up lunches at any school site. In an effort to enforce social distancing, there will be no eating on school sites.

post_text: PUHSD students will continue distance learning through May 1. Please visit our home page at puhsd.us for more information.
shared_text:
Placer County Office of Education
March 26 at 12:06 PM ¬∑

Placer County school leaders in concurrence with Placer County Public Health extend closures of all public schools and state preschools in Placer County through May 1, 2020 in order to slow the spread of COVID-19 to the maximum extent possible. Read the press release: bit.ly/PlacerSchoolsExtClosure

Parents, students and families will continue to receive updates and information from their school districts and charter schools regularly through email, by phone and through social media. School facilities will stay open to staff for essential tasks, and education will continue through district distance learning plans. Schools will continue to provide meals and childcare, when possible.

The Placer County Office of Education's Childcare Resource and Referral Program is available for families working in essential services. Call (530) 745-1380 for assistance.
#goldineducation #wearepcoe

post_text:
Many thanks to Coalition for Auburn and Lincoln Youth for always looking out for our communities -- especially our youth‚ù§Ô∏è

As our students and all of us are navigating these uncertain and stressful times, it's important to keep a pulse on everyone's mental health, and offer love and support wherever and whenever we can. #togetherwearestrong
shared_text:
Renee Silvera Berg shared a post to the group: Loomis Community Post.
March 23 at 2:16 PM ¬∑

Mental health is very important for all of us. It actually helps us stay physically healthy as well. Please check out the following tips that are good for children and adults, especially in these times of uncertainty.

Coalition for Auburn and Lincoln Youth
March 23 at 1:52 PM ¬∑

During this unprecedented time, we will be sharing even more resources to help keep our youth free from substance use and have every opportunity to grow up healthy and with a positive vision for their future.

Lighthouse Counseling & Family Resource Center is one such resource. Check out these great tips to help children who may be worried about Coronavirus:

15 WAYS WE CAN HELP KIDS WHO ARE WORRIED ABOUT CORONAVIRUS
1) Be available to talk
2) Acknowledge worries
3) Limit news exposure
4) Stick to routines & set boundaries
5) Start or continue mindful practices
6) Set & track daily goals or habits
7) Practice controlled breathing
8) Try progressive muscle relaxation
9) Use grounding strategies
10) Set a timer for worries
11) Write a story or draw a picture about defeating worries
12) Use a journal or feelings tracker
13) Avoid participating in worry rituals
14) Avoid excessive reassurance
15) Be mindful of your own worries

https://www.counselorkeri.com/2020/03/14/talk-to-kids-about-coronavirus/
Coalition For Placer Youth

URGENT UPDATE FOR PUHSD FAMILIES AND COMMUNITY

March 15, 2020

This afternoon, Governor Newsom delivered a new proclamation providing additional restrictions and guidelines due to the ongoing Coronavirus COVID-19 public health emergency. In light of this, we feel it is prudent to close all PUHSD schools, effective tomorrow, Monday, March 16.

Additional information and messaging is being sent to our families and students this afternoon. Thank you to everyone in our communities for your continued support for our students throughout these unprecedented difficult times.

On behalf of our PUHSD and Confluence High School teams, we can't thank our community enough for your incredibly thoughtful and generous holiday gifts to our students.

Many thanks to Dutch Bros Coffee owner Heather Mauel, who reached out to our community to ask for help with this incredible project. The pure joy on more than 70 faces reflected their feelings of acceptance and love. From guitars and amplifiers to comforters, shoes, warm jackets and more, the room was filled with cheer and a feeling of belonging. We even had a wrapping paper fashion show and lots of good food. Thank you so much for making a difference in our youth's lives. #yourock‚ù§Ô∏è Isaak Egge Melany Paul-Hall

Congratulations to our students and their teacher, Jonathan Schwartz, for his continued leadership and inspiration to our students.

Thank you Lemelson-MIT Program for giving so many high school students this opportunity to shine!
